properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Shower activity will continue for the rest of the weekend as the low pressure system slow tracks through the region. Additional rainfall amounts of 10 to 20 mm are forecast through the remainder of the weekend. Rainfall warnings remain in effect for northern New Brunswick. This rainfall combined with snowmelt north of the region will enhance the threat of flooding. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Update: A High Water Advisory Continues For The Saskatchewan And Carrot Rivers Near The Town Of The Pas
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre continues to issue a High Water Advisory for the Saskatchewan and Carrot Rivers near the Town of The Pas. River levels are currently rising which may cause ice jamming during the melt and ice break-up period. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-04-21T10:30:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-04-20T10:22:37-05:00, 0413C5EB-3834-D4CC-DCA1-B7C772E40318
Area: The Saskatchewan and Carrot Rivers near the Town of The Pas

properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Continues For The Red River From Emerson To The Red River Floodway Channel Inlet
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre continues to issue a Flood Warning on the Red River from Emerson to the Red River Floodway channel inlet due to high water flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions given by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rainfall, combined with melting snow, is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. Significant rainfall, mild temperatures, and snow melt are expected Sunday through Sunday night. Showers are forecast to intensify Sunday into Sunday night with rainfall amounts of 15 to 25 mm expected by early Monday morning. The potential for higher amounts exists, especially over higher elevations where accumulations could reach and potentially exceed 50 mm. Furthermore, the rain will combine with mild temperatures to cause significant snowmelt and an increased potential for localized flooding. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-04-21T10:35:11-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-04-20T18:36:11-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0296892121.2019

properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, heavy at times is expected. The ground, already near saturation, has little ability to absorb further rainfall. Rain will continue today. Rainfall amounts of 20 to 30 mm have already been reported. An additional 5 to 10 mm of rain is expected today. Rain will taper off to drizzle this evening. This rainfall is the result of a second low pressure system tracking northeastward over the region from the Southern Plains States. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
